# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-route53
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-route53/anycast] The first documented use of anycast routing for topological load-balancing of Internet-connected services was in 1989; the technique was first formally documented in the IETF four years later.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] It was first applied to critical infrastructure in 2001 with the anycasting of the I-root nameserver.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Early objections to the deployment of anycast routing centered on the perceived conflict between long-lived TCP connections and the volatility of the Internet's routed topology.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] In practice, such problems were not observed, and these objections dissipated by the early 2000s.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Many initial anycast deployments consisted of DNS servers, using principally UDP transport.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Measurements of long-term anycast flows revealed very few failures due to mid-connection instance switches, far fewer (less than 0.017% or "less than one flow per ten thousand per hour of duration" according to various sources) than were attributed to other causes of failure.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Numerous mechanisms were developed to efficiently share state between anycast instances.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] And some TCP-based protocols, notably HTTP, incorporated "redirect" mechanisms, whereby anycast service addresses could be used to locate the nearest instance of a service, whereupon a user would be redirected to that specific instance prior to the initiation of any long-lived stateful transaction.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Anycast is implemented in the Internet via Border Gateway Protocol (BGP), where multiple hosts (usually in different geographic areas) are given the same anycast IP address and they all announce it to their BGP table.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Routers consider these to be alternative routes to the same destination, even though they are actually routes to different destinations with the same address.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Routers will often select the path with fewer hops, which leads to the one closer to the client as being selected (often faster).
[src:aws-route53/anycast] It doesn't always happen, as some routers will choose other metrics (least congested, cheapest).
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Anycast is supported explicitly in the IPv6 addressing architecture.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] The lowest address within an IPv6 subnet (interface identifier 0) is reserved as the "Subnet Router" anycast address.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] In addition, the highest 128 interface identifiers within a subnet are also reserved as anycast addresses.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] The method used in IPv4 of advertising multiple routes in BGP to multiply-assigned unicast addresses also still works in IPv6, and can be used to route packets to the nearest of several geographically dispersed hosts with the same address.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] This approach, which does not depend on anycast-aware routers, has the same use cases together with the same problems and limitations as in IPv4.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] With the growth of the Internet, network services increasingly have high-availability requirements.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] As a result, operation of anycast services has grown in popularity among network operators.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] All Internet root nameservers are implemented as clusters of hosts using anycast addressing.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] All 13 root servers A–M exist in multiple locations, with 11 on multiple continents.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] (Root servers B and H exist in two U.S. locations.) The servers use anycast address announcements to provide a decentralized service.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] This has accelerated the deployment of physical (rather than logical) root servers outside the United States.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Many commercial DNS providers have switched to an IP anycast environment to increase query performance and redundancy, and to implement load balancing.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] In IPv4 to IPv6 transitioning, anycast addressing may be deployed to provide IPv6 compatibility to IPv4 hosts.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] This method, 6to4, uses a default gateway with the IP address *192.88.99.1*.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] This allows multiple providers to implement 6to4 gateways without hosts having to know each individual provider's gateway addresses.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] 6to4 has been deprecated in response to native IPv6 becoming more prevalent.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Content delivery networks may use anycast for actual HTTP connections to their distribution centers, or for DNS.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Because most HTTP connections to such networks request static content such as images and style sheets, they are generally short-lived and stateless across subsequent TCP sessions.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] The general stability of routes and statelessness of connections makes anycast suitable for this application, even though it uses TCP.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Anycast rendezvous point can be used in Multicast Source Discovery Protocol (MSDP) and its advantageous application as Anycast RP is an intra-domain feature that provides redundancy and load-sharing capabilities.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] If the multiple anycast rendezvous point is used, IP routing automatically will select the topologically closest rendezvous point for each source and receiver.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] It would provide a multicast network with the fault tolerance requirements.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Anycast allows any operator whose routing information is accepted by an intermediate router to hijack any packets intended for the anycast address.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] While this at first sight appears insecure, it is no different from the routing of ordinary IP packets, and no more or less secure.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] As with conventional IP routing, careful filtering of who is and is not allowed to propagate route announcements is crucial to prevent man-in-the-middle or blackhole attacks.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] The former can also be prevented by encrypting and authenticating messages, such as using Transport Layer Security, while the latter can be frustrated by onion routing.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Anycast is normally highly reliable, as it can provide automatic failover without adding complexity or new potential points of failure.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Anycast applications typically feature external "heartbeat" monitoring of the server's function, and withdraw the route announcement if the server fails.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] In some cases this is done by the actual servers announcing the anycast prefix to the router over OSPF or another IGP.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] If the servers die, the router will automatically withdraw the announcement.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] "Heartbeat" functionality is important because, if the announcement continues for a failed server, the server will act as a "black hole" for nearby clients; this is the most serious mode of failure for an anycast system.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Even in this event, this kind of failure will only cause a total failure for clients that are closer to this server than any other, and will not cause a global failure.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] However, even the automation necessary to implement "heartbeat" routing withdrawal can itself add a potential point of failure, as seen in the 2021 Facebook outage.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] In denial-of-service attacks, a rogue network host may advertise itself as an anycast server for a vital network service, to provide false information or simply block service.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Anycast methodologies on the Internet may be exploited to distribute DDoS attacks and reduce their effectiveness: As traffic is routed to the closest node, a process over which the attacker has no control, the DDoS traffic flow will be distributed amongst the closest nodes.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] This may be a reason to deploy anycast addressing.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] The effectiveness of this technique depends upon maintaining the secrecy of any unicast addresses associated with anycast service nodes, however, since an attacker in possession of the unicast addresses of individual nodes can attack them from any location, bypassing anycast addressing methods.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Some anycast deployments on the Internet distinguish between local and global nodes to benefit the local community, by addressing local nodes preferentially.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Local nodes are often announced with the no-export BGP community to prevent hosts from announcing them to their peers, i.e. the announcement is kept in the local area.
[src:aws-route53/anycast] Where both local and global nodes are deployed, the announcements from global nodes are often AS prepended (i.e. the AS is added a few more times) to make the path longer so that a local node announcement is preferred over a global node announcement.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] A **DNS zone** is a specific portion of the DNS namespace in the Domain Name System (DNS), which a specific organization or administrator manages.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] A DNS zone is an administrative space allowing more granular control of the DNS components, such as authoritative nameserver.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] The DNS is broken up into different zones, distinctly managed areas in the DNS namespace.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] DNS zones are not necessarily physically separated from one another; however, a DNS zone can contain multiple subdomains, and multiple zones can exist on the same server.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] The domain namespace of the Internet is organized into a hierarchical layout of subdomains below the DNS root domain.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] The individual domains of this tree may serve as delegation points for administrative authority and management.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] However, it is usually desirable to implement fine-grained delegation boundaries so that multiple sub-levels of a domain may be managed independently.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] Therefore, the domain name space is partitioned into areas (*zones*) for this purpose.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] A zone starts at a domain and extends downward in the tree to the leaf nodes or to the top-level of subdomains where other zones start.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] A DNS zone is implemented in the configuration system of a domain name server.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] Historically, it is defined in the zone file, an operating system text file that starts with the special DNS record type *Start of Authority* (SOA) and contains all records for the resources described within the zone.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] This format was originally used by the Berkeley Internet Name Domain Server (BIND) software package and is defined in RFC 1034 and RFC 1035.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] Most top-level domain name registry operators offer their namespaces to the public or entities with the mandated geographic or otherwise scoped purpose for registering second-level domains.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] Similarly, an organization in charge of a lower-level domain may operate its namespace and subdivide its space.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] Each registration or allocation of subdomain space obligates the registrant to maintain an administrative and technical infrastructure to manage the responsibility for its zone, including sub-delegation to lower-level domains.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] Each delegation confers essentially unrestricted technical autonomy over the allocated space.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] An area of one or more subdomains that have been delegated for management is called a DNS zone.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] A zone always starts at a domain boundary to include all leaf nodes (hosts) in the domain or ends at the boundary of another independently managed zone.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] As each domain is further divided into sub-domains, each becoming a DNS zone with its own set of administrators and DNS servers, the tree grows with the largest number of leaf nodes at the bottom.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] At this lowest level, in the end-nodes or leaves of the tree, the term *DNS zone* becomes essentially synonymous with the term "domain", both in terms of use and administration.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] The term *domain* is used in the business functions of the entity assigned to it, and the term *zone* is usually used for the configuration of DNS services.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] DNS zones contain the records for mapping domain names to IP addresses or other information.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] The resolution of a domain name to its assigned information is also referred to as *forward* resolution, and the DNS zones associated with such processes are often referred to as *forward* zones.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] The term arose as the opposite of *reverse* zones, which are used for the reverse process: finding the DNS name associated with an IP address.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] Such reverse zones are maintained in the Internet Address and Routing Parameter Area (domain arpa).
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] The top-level domain arpa serves as a delegation zone for various technical infrastructure aspects of DNS and the Internet, and does not implement the registration and delegation system of the country and generic domains.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] The name *arpa* is a remnant of the ARPANET, one of the predecessor stages of the Internet.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] Intended as a transitional aid to the DNS, deleting the domain arpa was later found to be impractical.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] Consequently, the name was officially redefined as an acronym for *Address and Routing Parameter Area*.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] It contains sub-zones used for reverse resolution of IP addresses to host names (IPv4: in-addr.arpa, IPv6: ip6.arpa), telephone number mapping (ENUM, e164.arpa), and uniform resource identifier resolution (uri.arpa, urn.arpa).
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] Although the administrative structure of this domain and its sub-domains is different, the technical delegation into zones of responsibility is similar and the DNS tools and servers used are identical to any other zone.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] Sub-zones are delegated by components of the respective resources.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] For example, 8.8.2.5.5.2.2.0.0.8.1.e164.arpa., which might represent an E.164 telephone number in the ENUM system, might be sub-delegated at suitable boundaries of the name.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] An example of an IP addresses in the reverse DNS zone is 166.188.77.208.in-addr.arpa, which represents the address 208.77.188.166 and resolves to the domain name *www.example.com*.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] In the case of IP addresses, the reverse zones are delegated to the Internet service provider (ISP) to which the IP address block is assigned.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] When an ISP allocates a range to a customer, it usually also delegates the management of that space to the customer by insertion of name server resource records pointing to the customer's DNS facilities into their zone, or provides other management tools.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] Allocations of single IP addresses for networks connected through network address translation (NAT) typically do not provide such facilities.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] As an example of the DNS resolving process, consider the role of a recursive DNS resolver attempting to look up the address "en.wikipedia.org.".
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] It begins with a list of addresses for the most authoritative name servers it knows about – the root zone name servers (indicated by the full stop or period), which contains name server information for all top-level domains (TLDs) of the Internet.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] When querying one of the root name servers, it is possible that the root zone will not directly contain a record for "en.wikipedia.org.", in which case it will provide a referral to the authoritative name servers for the "org." top-level domain (TLD).
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] The resolver is issued a referral to the authoritative name servers for the "org." zone, which it will contact for more specific information.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] Again when querying one of the "org." name servers, the resolver may be issued with another referral to the "wikipedia.org." zone, whereupon it will again query for "en.wikipedia.org.".
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] If the last name server queried did not contain authoritative data for the target of the CNAME, it would have issued the resolver with yet another referral, this time to the zone "text.wikimedia.org.".
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] However, since the resolver had previously determined the authoritative name servers for the zone "org.", it does not need to begin the resolution process from scratch but instead start at zone "org.", thus avoiding another query to the root name servers.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] There is no requirement that resolving should involve any referrals at all.
[src:aws-route53/dns-zone] Looking up "en.wikipedia.org." on the root name servers always results in referrals, but if an alternative DNS root is used which is set up to contain a record for "en.wikipedia.org.", then the record is returned on the first query.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The **Domain Name System** (**DNS**) is a hierarchical and distributed name service that provides a naming system for computers, services, and other resources on the Internet or other Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] It associates various information with *domain names* (identification strings) assigned to each of the associated entities.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Most prominently, it translates readily memorized domain names to the numerical IP addresses needed for locating and identifying computer services and devices with the underlying network protocols.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System has been an essential component of the functionality of the Internet since 1985.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System delegates the responsibility of assigning domain names and mapping those names to Internet resources by designating authoritative name servers for each domain.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Network administrators may delegate authority over subdomains of their allocated name space to other name servers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This mechanism provides distributed and fault-tolerant service and was designed to avoid a single large central database.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In addition, the DNS specifies the technical functionality of the database service that is at its core.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] It defines the DNS protocol, a detailed specification of the data structures and data communication exchanges used in the DNS, as part of the Internet protocol suite.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The Internet maintains two principal namespaces, the domain name hierarchy and the IP address spaces.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System maintains the domain name hierarchy and provides translation services between it and the address spaces.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Internet name servers and a communication protocol implement the Domain Name System.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A DNS name server is a server that stores the DNS records for a domain; a DNS name server responds with answers to queries against its database.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The most common types of records stored in the DNS database are for start of authority (SOA), IP addresses (A and AAAA), SMTP mail exchangers (MX), name servers (NS), pointers for reverse DNS lookups (PTR), and domain name aliases (CNAME).
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Although not intended to be a general-purpose database, DNS has been expanded over time to store records for other types of data for either automatic lookups, such as DNSSEC records, or for human queries such as *responsible person* (RP) records.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] As a general-purpose database, the DNS has also been used in combating unsolicited email (spam) by storing blocklists.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The DNS database is conventionally stored in a structured text file, the zone file, but other database systems are common.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System originally used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) as transport over IP.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Reliability, security, and privacy concerns spawned the use of the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) as well as numerous other protocol developments.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] An often-used analogy to explain the DNS is that it serves as the phone book for the Internet by translating human-friendly computer hostnames into IP addresses.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The DNS can be quickly and transparently updated, allowing a service's location on the network to change without affecting the end users, who continue to use the same hostname.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Users take advantage of this when they use meaningful Uniform Resource Locators (URLs) and e-mail addresses without having to know how the computer actually locates the services.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] An important and ubiquitous function of the DNS is its central role in distributed Internet services such as cloud services and content delivery networks.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] When a user accesses a distributed Internet service using a URL, the domain name of the URL is translated to the IP address of a server that is proximal to the user.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The key functionality of the DNS exploited here is that different users can *simultaneously* receive different translations for the *same* domain name, a key point of divergence from a traditional phone-book view of the DNS.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This process of using the DNS to assign proximal servers to users is key to providing faster and more reliable responses on the Internet and is widely used by most major Internet services.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The DNS reflects the structure of administrative responsibility on the Internet.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Each subdomain is a zone of administrative autonomy delegated to a manager.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] For zones operated by a registry, administrative information is often complemented by the registry's RDAP and WHOIS services.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] That data can be used to gain insight on, and track responsibility for, a given host on the Internet.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Using a simpler, more memorable name in place of a host's numerical address dates back to the ARPANET era.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The Stanford Research Institute (now SRI International) maintained a text file named HOSTS.TXT that mapped host names to the numerical addresses of computers on the ARPANET.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Elizabeth Feinler developed and maintained the first ARPANET directory.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Maintenance of numerical addresses, called the Assigned Numbers List, was handled by Jon Postel at the University of Southern California's Information Sciences Institute (ISI), whose team worked closely with SRI.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Computers, including their hostnames and addresses, were added to the primary file by contacting the SRI Network Information Center (NIC), directed by Feinler, via telephone during business hours.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Later, Feinler set up a WHOIS directory on a server in the NIC for retrieval of information about resources, contacts, and entities.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] She and her team developed the concept of domains.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Feinler suggested that domains should be based on the location of the physical address of the computer.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Computers at educational institutions would have the domain *edu*, for example.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] She and her team managed the Host Naming Registry from 1972 to 1989.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] By the early 1980s, maintaining a single, centralized host table had become slow and unwieldy and the emerging network required an automated naming system to address technical and personnel issues.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Postel directed the task of forging a compromise between five competing proposals of solutions to Paul Mockapetris.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Mockapetris instead created the Domain Name System in 1983 while at the University of Southern California.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The Internet Engineering Task Force published the original specifications in RFC 882 and RFC 883 in November 1983.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] These were updated in RFC 973 in January 1986.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In 1984, four UC Berkeley students, Douglas Terry, Mark Painter, David Riggle, and Songnian Zhou, wrote the first Unix name server implementation for the Berkeley Internet Name Domain, commonly referred to as BIND.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In 1985, Kevin Dunlap of DEC substantially revised the DNS implementation.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Mike Karels, Phil Almquist, and Paul Vixie then took over BIND maintenance.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Internet Systems Consortium was founded in 1994 by Rick Adams, Paul Vixie, and Carl Malamud, expressly to provide a home for BIND development and maintenance.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] BIND versions from 4.9.3 onward were developed and maintained by ISC, with support provided by ISC's sponsors.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] As co-architects/programmers, Bob Halley and Paul Vixie released the first production-ready version of BIND version 8 in May 1997.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Since 2000, over 43 different core developers have worked on BIND.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In November 1987, RFC 1034 and RFC 1035 superseded the 1983 DNS specifications.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Several additional Request for Comments have proposed extensions to the core DNS protocols.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The domain name space consists of a tree data structure.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Each node or leaf in the tree has a *label* and zero or more *resource records* (RR), which hold information associated with the domain name.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The domain name itself consists of the label, concatenated with the name of its parent node on the right, separated by a dot.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The tree sub-divides into *zones* beginning at the root zone.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A DNS zone may consist of as many domains and subdomains as the zone manager chooses.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNS can also be partitioned according to *class* where the separate classes can be thought of as an array of parallel namespace trees.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Administrative responsibility for any zone may be divided by creating additional zones.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Authority over the new zone is said to be *delegated* to a designated name server.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The parent zone ceases to be authoritative for the new zone.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The definitive descriptions of the rules for forming domain names appear in RFC 1035, RFC 1123, RFC 2181, and RFC 5892.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A domain name consists of one or more parts, technically called *labels*, that are conventionally concatenated, and delimited by dots, such as example.com.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The right-most label conveys the top-level domain; for example, the domain name www.example.com belongs to the top-level domain *com*.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The hierarchy of domains descends from right to left; each label to the left specifies a subdivision, or subdomain of the domain to the right.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] For example, the label *example* specifies a subdomain of the *com* domain, and *www* is a subdomain of example.com.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This tree of subdivisions may have up to 127 levels.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A label may contain zero to 63 characters, because the length is only allowed to take 6 bits.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The null label of length zero is reserved for the root zone.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The full domain name may not exceed the length of 253 characters in its textual representation (or 254 with the trailing dot).
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In the internal binary representation of the DNS this maximum length of 253 requires 255 octets of storage, as it also stores the length of the first of many labels and adds last null byte.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] 255 length is only achieved with at least 6 labels (counting the last null label).
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Although no technical limitation exists to prevent domain name labels from using any character that is representable by an octet, hostnames use a preferred format and character set.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The characters allowed in labels are a subset of the ASCII character set, consisting of characters *a* through *z*, *A* through *Z*, digits *0* through *9*, and hyphen.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This rule is known as the *LDH rule* (letters, digits, hyphen).
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Domain names are interpreted in a case-independent manner.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Labels may not start or end with a hyphen.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] An additional rule requires that top-level domain names should not be all-numeric.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The limited set of ASCII characters permitted in the DNS prevented the representation of names and words of many languages in their native alphabets or scripts.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] To make this possible, ICANN approved the Internationalizing Domain Names in Applications (IDNA) system, by which user applications, such as web browsers, map Unicode strings into the valid DNS character set using Punycode.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In 2009, ICANN approved the installation of internationalized domain name country code top-level domains (*ccTLD*s).
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In addition, many registries of the existing top-level domain names (*TLD*s) have adopted the IDNA system, guided by RFC 5890, RFC 5891, RFC 5892, RFC 5893.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System is maintained by a distributed database system, which uses the client–server model.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The nodes of this database are the name servers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Each domain has at least one authoritative DNS server that publishes information about that domain and the name servers of any domains subordinate to it.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The top of the hierarchy is served by the root name servers, the servers to query when looking up (*resolving*) a TLD.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] An authoritative name server can either be a *primary* server or a *secondary* server.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Historically the terms *master/slave* and *primary/secondary* were sometimes used interchangeably but the current practice is to use the latter form.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A primary server is a server that stores the original copies of all zone records.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A secondary server uses a special automatic updating mechanism in the DNS protocol in communication with its primary to maintain an identical copy of the primary records.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Every DNS zone must be assigned a set of authoritative name servers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This set of servers is stored in the parent domain zone with name server (NS) records.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] An authoritative server indicates its status of supplying definitive answers, deemed *authoritative*, by setting a protocol flag, called the "*Authoritative Answer*" (*AA*) bit in its responses.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] When a name server is designated as the authoritative server for a domain name for which it does not have authoritative data, it presents a type of error called a "lame delegation" or "lame response".
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Domain name resolvers determine the domain name servers responsible for the domain name in question by a sequence of queries starting with the right-most (top-level) domain label.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] For proper operation of its domain name resolver, a network host is configured with an initial cache (*hints*) of the known addresses of the root name servers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The hints are updated periodically by an administrator by retrieving a dataset from a reliable source.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Assuming the resolver has no cached records to accelerate the process, the resolution process starts with a query to one of the root servers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In typical operation, the root servers do not answer directly, but respond with a referral to more authoritative servers, e.g., a query for "www.wikipedia.org" is referred to the *org* servers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The resolver now queries the servers referred to, and iteratively repeats this process until it receives an authoritative answer.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The diagram illustrates this process for the host that is named by the fully qualified domain name "www.wikipedia.org".
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This mechanism would place a large traffic burden on the root servers, if every resolution on the Internet required starting at the root.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In practice caching is used in DNS servers to off-load the root servers, and as a result, root name servers actually are involved in only a relatively small fraction of all requests.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In theory, authoritative name servers are sufficient for the operation of the Internet.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] However, with only authoritative name servers operating, every DNS query must start with recursive queries at the root zone of the Domain Name System and each user system would have to implement resolver software capable of recursive operation.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Typically, such caching DNS servers also implement the recursive algorithm necessary to resolve a given name starting with the DNS root through to the authoritative name servers of the queried domain.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] With this function implemented in the name server, user applications gain efficiency in design and operation.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The combination of DNS caching and recursive functions in a name server is not mandatory; the functions can be implemented independently in servers for special purposes.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Internet service providers (ISP) typically provide recursive and caching name servers for their customers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In addition, many home networking routers implement DNS caches and recursion to improve efficiency in the local network.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The client side of the DNS is called a DNS resolver.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A resolver is responsible for initiating and sequencing the queries that ultimately lead to a full resolution (translation) of the resource sought, e.g., translation of a domain name into an IP address.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers are classified by a variety of query methods, such as *recursive*, *non-recursive*, and *iterative*.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A resolution process may use a combination of these methods.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In a *non-recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a DNS server that provides a record either for which the server is authoritative, or it provides a partial result without querying other servers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In case of a caching DNS resolver, the non-recursive query of its local DNS cache delivers a result and reduces the load on upstream DNS servers by caching DNS resource records for a period of time after an initial response from upstream DNS servers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In a *recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a single DNS server, which may in turn query other DNS servers on behalf of the requester.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] For example, a simple stub resolver running on a home router typically makes a recursive query to the DNS server run by the user's ISP.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A recursive query is one for which the DNS server answers the query completely by querying other name servers as needed.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In typical operation, a client issues a recursive query to a caching recursive DNS server, which subsequently issues non-recursive queries to determine the answer and send a single answer back to the client.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The resolver, or another DNS server acting recursively on behalf of the resolver, negotiates use of recursive service using bits in the query headers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNS servers are not required to support recursive queries.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The *iterative query* procedure is a process in which a DNS resolver queries a chain of one or more DNS servers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Each server refers the client to the next server in the chain, until the current server can fully resolve the request.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] For example, a possible resolution of www.example.com would query a global root server, then a "com" server, and finally an "example.com" server.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Name servers in delegations are identified by name, rather than by IP address.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This means that a resolving name server must issue another DNS request to discover the IP address of the server to which it has been referred.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] If the name given in the delegation is a subdomain of the domain for which the delegation is being provided, there is a circular dependency.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In this case, the name server providing the delegation must also provide one or more IP addresses for the authoritative name server mentioned in the delegation.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The delegating name server provides this glue in the form of records in the *additional section* of the DNS response, and provides the delegation in the *authority section* of the response.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A glue record is a combination of the name server and IP address.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] For example, if the authoritative name server for example.org is ns1.example.org, a computer trying to resolve www.example.org first resolves ns1.example.org.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] As ns1 is contained in example.org, this requires resolving example.org first, which presents a circular dependency.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] To break the dependency, the name server for the top level domain org includes glue along with the delegation for example.org.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The glue records are address records that provide IP addresses for ns1.example.org.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The resolver uses one or more of these IP addresses to query one of the domain's authoritative servers, which allows it to complete the DNS query.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A common approach to reduce the query load on DNS servers is to cache the results of name resolution locally or on intermediary resolver hosts.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Each DNS query result comes with a time to live (TTL), which indicates how long the information remains valid before it needs to be discarded or refreshed.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This TTL is determined by the administrator of the authoritative DNS server and can range from a few seconds to several days or even weeks.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] As a result of this distributed caching architecture, changes to DNS records do not propagate throughout the network immediately, but require all caches to expire and to be refreshed after the TTL.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] RFC 1912 conveys basic rules for determining appropriate TTL values.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Some resolvers may override TTL values, as the protocol supports caching for up to sixty-eight years or no caching at all.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Negative caching, i.e. the caching of the fact of non-existence of a record, is determined by name servers authoritative for a zone which must include the Start of Authority (SOA) record when reporting no data of the requested type exists.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The value of the *minimum* field of the SOA record and the TTL of the SOA itself is used to establish the TTL for the negative answer.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A reverse DNS lookup is a query of the DNS for domain names when the IP address is known.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Multiple domain names may be associated with an IP address.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The DNS stores IP addresses in the form of domain names as specially formatted names in pointer (PTR) records within the infrastructure top-level domain arpa.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] For IPv6, the reverse lookup domain is ip6.arpa.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The IP address is represented as a name in reverse-ordered octet representation for IPv4, and reverse-ordered nibble representation for IPv6.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] When performing a reverse lookup, the DNS client converts the address into these formats before querying the name for a PTR record following the delegation chain as for any DNS query.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] For example, assuming the IPv4 address 208.80.152.2 is assigned to Wikimedia, it is represented as a DNS name in reverse order: 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] When the DNS resolver gets a pointer (PTR) request, it begins by querying the root servers, which point to the servers of American Registry for Internet Numbers (ARIN) for the 208.in-addr.arpa zone.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] ARIN's servers delegate 152.80.208.in-addr.arpa to Wikimedia to which the resolver sends another query for 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa, which results in an authoritative response.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Users generally do not communicate directly with a DNS resolver.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Instead DNS resolution takes place transparently in applications such as web browsers, e-mail clients, and other Internet applications.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] When an application makes a request that requires a domain name lookup, such programs send a resolution request to the DNS resolver in the local operating system, which in turn handles the communications required.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The DNS resolver will almost invariably have a cache (see above) containing recent lookups.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] If the cache can provide the answer to the request, the resolver will return the value in the cache to the program that made the request.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] If the cache does not contain the answer, the resolver will send the request to one or more designated DNS servers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In any event, the name server thus queried will follow the process outlined above, until it either successfully finds a result or does not.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] It then returns its results to the DNS resolver; assuming it has found a result, the resolver duly caches that result for future use, and hands the result back to the software which initiated the request.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Some large ISPs have configured their DNS servers to violate rules, such as by disobeying TTLs, or by indicating that a domain name does not exist just because one of its name servers does not respond.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Some applications such as web browsers maintain an internal DNS cache to avoid repeated lookups via the network.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This practice can add extra difficulty when debugging DNS issues as it obscures the history of such data.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] These caches typically use very short caching times on the order of one minute.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer represents a notable exception: versions up to IE 3.x cache DNS records for 24 hours by default.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer 4.x and later versions (up to IE 8) decrease the default timeout value to half an hour, which may be changed by modifying the default configuration.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] When Google Chrome detects issues with the DNS server it displays a specific error message.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System includes several other functions and features.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Hostnames and IP addresses are not required to match in a one-to-one relationship.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Multiple hostnames may correspond to a single IP address, which is useful in virtual hosting, in which many web sites are served from a single host.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Alternatively, a single hostname may resolve to many IP addresses to facilitate fault tolerance and load distribution to multiple server instances across an enterprise or the global Internet.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNS serves other purposes in addition to translating names to IP addresses.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] For instance, mail transfer agents use DNS to find the best mail server to deliver e-mail: An MX record provides a mapping between a domain and a mail exchanger; this can provide an additional layer of fault tolerance and load distribution.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The DNS is used for efficient storage and distribution of IP addresses of block-listed email hosts.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A common method is to place the IP address of the subject host into the sub-domain of a higher level domain name, and to resolve that name to a record that indicates a positive or a negative indication.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] E-mail servers can query blocklist.example to find out if a specific host connecting to them is in the block list.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Many such block lists, either subscription-based or free of cost, are available for use by email administrators and anti-spam software.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] To provide resilience in the event of computer or network failure, multiple DNS servers are usually provided for coverage of each domain.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] At the top level of global DNS, thirteen groups of root name servers exist, with additional "copies" of them distributed worldwide via anycast addressing.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS (DDNS) updates a DNS server with a client IP address on-the-fly, for example, when moving between ISPs or mobile hot spots, or when the IP address changes administratively.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The DNS protocol uses two types of DNS messages, queries and responses; both have the same format.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Each message consists of a header and four sections: question, answer, authority, and an additional space.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A header field (*flags*) controls the content of these four sections.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The header section consists of the following fields: *Identification*, *Flags*, *Number of questions*, *Number of answers*, *Number of authority resource records* (RRs), and *Number of additional RRs*.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Each field is 16 bits long, and appears in the order given.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The identification field is used to match responses with queries.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] After the flags word, the header ends with four 16-bit integers which contain the number of records in each of the sections that follow, in the same order.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Indicates if the message is a query (0) or a reply (1).
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The type can be QUERY (standard query, 0), IQUERY (inverse query, 1), or STATUS (server status request, 2).
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Authoritative Answer, in a response, indicates if the DNS server is authoritative for the queried hostname.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] TrunCation, indicates that this message was truncated due to excessive length.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Recursion Desired, indicates if the client means a recursive query.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Recursion Available, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server supports recursion.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Authentic Data, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server verified the data.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Checking Disabled, in a query, indicates that non-verified data is acceptable in a response.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Response code, can be NOERROR (0), FORMERR (1, Format error), SERVFAIL (2), NXDOMAIN (3, Nonexistent domain), etc.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The question section has a simpler format than the resource record format used in the other sections.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The domain name is broken into discrete labels which are concatenated; each label is prefixed by the length of that label.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System specifies a database of information elements for network resources.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The types of information elements are categorized and organized with a list of DNS record types, the resource records (RRs).
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Each record has a type (name and number), an expiration time (time to live), a class, and type-specific data.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Resource records of the same type are described as a *resource record set* (RRset), having no special ordering.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers return the entire set upon query, but servers may implement round-robin ordering to achieve load balancing.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In contrast, the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) work on the complete set of resource record in canonical order.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The *CLASS* of a record is set to IN (for *Internet*) for common DNS records involving Internet hostnames, servers, or IP addresses.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In addition, the classes Chaos (CH) and Hesiod (HS) exist.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Each class is an independent name space with potentially different delegations of DNS zones.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In addition to resource records defined in a zone file, the domain name system also defines several request types that are used only in communication with other DNS nodes (*on the wire*), such as when performing zone transfers (AXFR/IXFR) or for EDNS (OPT).
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The domain name system supports wildcard DNS records which specify names that start with the *asterisk label*, `*`, e.g., `*.example`.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNS records belonging to wildcard domain names specify rules for generating resource records within a single DNS zone by substituting whole labels with matching components of the query name, including any specified descendants.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] For example, in the following configuration, the DNS zone *x.example* specifies that all subdomains, including subdomains of subdomains, of *x.example* use the mail exchanger (MX) *a.x.example*.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The AAAA record for *a.x.example* is needed to specify the mail exchanger IP address.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] As this has the result of excluding this domain name and its subdomains from the wildcard matches, an additional MX record for the subdomain *a.x.example*, as well as a wildcarded MX record for all of its subdomains, must also be defined in the DNS zone.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The role of wildcard records was refined in RFC 4592, because the original definition in RFC 1034 was incomplete and resulted in misinterpretations by implementers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The original DNS protocol had limited provisions for extension with new features.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In 1999, Paul Vixie published in RFC 2671 (superseded by RFC 6891) an extension mechanism, called Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS) that introduced optional protocol elements without increasing overhead when not in use.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This was accomplished through the OPT pseudo-resource record that only exists in wire transmissions of the protocol, but not in any zone files.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Initial extensions were also suggested (EDNS0), such as increasing the DNS message size in UDP datagrams.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS updates use the UPDATE DNS opcode to add or remove resource records dynamically from a zone database maintained on an authoritative DNS server.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This facility is useful to register network clients into the DNS when they boot or become otherwise available on the network.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] As a booting client may be assigned a different IP address each time from a DHCP server, it is not possible to provide static DNS assignments for such clients.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] From the time of its origin in 1983 the DNS has used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) for transport over IP.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Its limitations have motivated numerous protocol developments for reliability, security, privacy, and other criteria, in the following decades.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] UDP reserves port number 53 for servers listening to queries.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Such a query consists of a clear-text request sent in a single UDP packet from the client, responded to with a clear-text reply sent in a single UDP packet from the server.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] When the length of the answer exceeds 512 bytes and both client and server support Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS), larger UDP packets may be used.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Use of DNS over UDP is limited by, among other things, its lack of transport-layer encryption, authentication, reliable delivery, and message length.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In 1989, RFC 1123 specified optional Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) transport for DNS queries, replies and, particularly, zone transfers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Via fragmentation of long replies, TCP allows longer responses, reliable delivery, and re-use of long-lived connections between clients and servers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] For larger responses, the server refers the client to TCP transport.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNS over TLS emerged as an IETF standard for encrypted DNS in 2016, utilizing Transport Layer Security (TLS) to protect the entire connection, rather than just the DNS payload.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] RFC 7858 specifies that opportunistic encryption and authenticated encryption may be supported, but did not make either server or client authentication mandatory.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNS over HTTPS was developed as a competing standard for DNS query transport in 2018, tunneling DNS query data over HTTPS, which transports HTTP over TLS.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DoH was promoted as a more web-friendly alternative to DNS since, like DNSCrypt, it uses TCP port 443, and thus looks similar to web traffic, though they are easily differentiable in practice without proper padding.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] RFC 9250, published in 2022 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over QUIC.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] It has "privacy properties similar to DNS over TLS (DoT) [...], and latency characteristics similar to classic DNS over UDP".
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This method is not the same as DNS over HTTP/3.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] RFC 9953, published in 2026 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over CoAP.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The "application use case of DoC is inspired by DNS over HTTPS (DoH) (RFC 8484).
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] However, DoC aims for deployment in the constrained Internet of Things (IoT), which usually conflicts with the requirements introduced by HTTPS." DoC outperforms other DNS resolution mechanisms in constrained scenarios.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Oblivious DNS (ODNS) was invented and implemented by researchers at Princeton University and the University of Chicago as an extension to unencrypted DNS, before DoH was standardized and widely deployed.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Apple and Cloudflare subsequently deployed the technology in the context of DoH, as Oblivious DoH (ODoH).
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] ODoH combines ingress/egress separation (invented in ODNS) with DoH's HTTPS tunneling and TLS transport-layer encryption in a single protocol.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNS may be run over virtual private networks (VPNs) and tunneling protocols.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The privacy gains of Oblivious DNS can be garnered through the use of the preexisting Tor network of ingress and egress nodes, paired with the transport-layer encryption provided by TLS.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt uses either TCP port 443, the same port as HTTPS encrypted web traffic, or UDP port 443.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This introduced not only privacy regarding the content of the query, but also a significant measure of firewall-traversal capability.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Privacy of user/query pairs is created, since the ingress node does not know the content of the query, while the egress node does not know the identity of the client.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt was first implemented in production by OpenDNS in December 2011.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] There are several free and open source software implementations that additionally integrate ODoH.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] It is available for a variety of operating systems, including Unix, Apple iOS, Linux, Android, and Windows.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Originally, security concerns were not major design considerations for DNS software or any software for deployment on the early Internet, as the network was not open for participation by the general public.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] However, the expansion of the Internet into the commercial sector in the 1990s changed the requirements for security measures to protect data integrity and user authentication.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Several vulnerability issues were discovered and exploited by malicious users.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] One such issue is DNS cache poisoning, in which data is distributed to caching resolvers under the pretense of being an authoritative origin server, thereby polluting the data store with potentially false information and long expiration times (time-to-live).
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Subsequently, legitimate application requests may be redirected to network hosts operated with malicious intent.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNS responses traditionally do not have a cryptographic signature, leading to many attack possibilities; the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) modify DNS to add support for cryptographically signed responses.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNSCurve has been proposed as an alternative to DNSSEC.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Other extensions, such as TSIG, add support for cryptographic authentication between trusted peers and are commonly used to authorize zone transfer or dynamic update operations.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Techniques such as forward-confirmed reverse DNS can also be used to help validate DNS results.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNS can also "leak" from otherwise secure or private connections, if attention is not paid to their configuration, and at times DNS has been used to bypass firewalls by malicious persons, and exfiltrate data, since it is often seen as innocuous.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Some domain names may be used to achieve spoofing effects.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] For example, paypal.com and paypa1.com are different names, yet users may be unable to distinguish them in a graphical user interface depending on the user's chosen typeface.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In many fonts the letter *l* and the numeral *1* look very similar or even identical.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This problem, known as the IDN homograph attack, is acute in systems that support internationalized domain names, as many character codes in ISO 10646 may appear identical on typical computer screens.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This vulnerability is occasionally exploited in phishing.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger is a type of cyber attack technique that uses the DNS to communicate and control malware remotely without relying on conventional protocols that might raise red flags.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The DNSMessenger attack is covert because DNS is primarily used for domain name resolution and is often not closely monitored by network security tools, making it an effective channel for attackers to exploit.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This technique involves the use of DNS TXT records to send commands to infected systems.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Once malware has been surreptitiously installed on a victim's machine, it reaches out to a controlled domain to retrieve commands encoded in DNS text records.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This form of malware communication is stealthy, as DNS requests are usually allowed through firewalls, and because DNS traffic is often seen as benign, these communications can bypass many network security defenses.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger attacks can enable a wide array of malicious activities, from data exfiltration to the delivery of additional payloads, all while remaining under the radar of traditional network security measures.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Understanding and defending against such methods are crucial for maintaining robust cybersecurity.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Originally designed as a public, hierarchical, distributed and heavily cached database, the DNS protocol has no confidentiality controls.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] User queries and nameserver responses are sent unencrypted, enabling network packet sniffing, DNS hijacking, DNS cache poisoning and man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] This deficiency is commonly used by cybercriminals and network operators for marketing purposes, user authentication on captive portals and censorship.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] User privacy is further exposed by proposals for increasing the level of client IP information in DNS queries (RFC 7871) for the benefit of content delivery networks.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Solutions preventing DNS inspection by the local network operator have been criticized for thwarting corporate network security policies and Internet censorship.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Public DNS servers are also criticized for contributing to the centralization of the Internet by placing control over DNS resolution in the hands of the few large companies which can afford to run public resolvers.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The right to use a domain name is delegated by domain name registrars which are accredited by the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICANN) or other organizations such as OpenNIC, that are charged with overseeing the name and number systems of the Internet.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In addition to ICANN, each top-level domain (TLD) is maintained and serviced technically by an administrative organization, operating a registry.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A *registry* is responsible for operating the database of names within its authoritative zone, although the term is most often used for TLDs.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] A *registrant* is a person or organization who asked for domain registration.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The registry receives registration information from each domain name *registrar*, which is authorized (accredited) to assign names in the corresponding zone and publishes the information using the WHOIS protocol.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] As of 2015, usage of RDAP is being considered.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] ICANN publishes the complete list of TLDs, TLD registries, and domain name registrars.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Registrant information associated with domain names is maintained in an online database accessible with the WHOIS service.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] For most of the more than 290 country code top-level domains (ccTLDs), the domain registries maintain the WHOIS (Registrant, name servers, expiration dates, etc.) information.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] For instance, DENIC, Germany NIC, holds the DE domain data.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] From about 2001, most generic top-level domain (gTLD) registries have adopted this so-called *thick* registry approach, i.e. keeping the WHOIS data in central registries instead of registrar databases.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] For top-level domains on COM and NET, a *thin* registry model is used.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The domain registry (GoDaddy, BigRock and PDR, VeriSign, etc.) holds basic WHOIS data (i.e., registrar and name servers, etc.).
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] On the other hand, organizations, i.e., registrants using ORG, are on the Public Interest Registry exclusively.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] Some domain name registries, often called *network information centers* (NIC), also function as registrars to end-users, in addition to providing access to the WHOIS datasets.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The top-level domain registries, such as for the domains COM, NET, and ORG use a registry-registrar model consisting of many domain name registrars.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] In this method of management, the registry only manages the domain name database and the relationship with the registrars.
[src:aws-route53/domain-name-system] The *registrants* (users of a domain name) are customers of the registrar, in some cases through additional subcontracting of resellers.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] A **name server** is a computer application that implements a network service for providing responses to queries against a directory service.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] It translates an often humanly meaningful, text-based identifier to a system-internal, often numeric identification or addressing component.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] This service is performed by the server in response to a service protocol request.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] An example of a name server is the server component of the Domain Name System (DNS), the core namespaces of the Internet.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] The most important function of DNS servers is the translation (resolution) of human-memorable domain names and hostnames into the corresponding numeric Internet Protocol (IP) addresses, which can be routed in the Internet.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] The Internet maintains two principal namespaces: the domain name hierarchy and the IP address system.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] The Domain Name System maintains the domain namespace and provides translation services between these two namespaces.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] Internet name servers implement the Domain Name System.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] The top hierarchy of the Domain Name System is served by the root name servers maintained by delegation by the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICANN).
[src:aws-route53/name-server] DNS servers, which are located all over the world, translate domain names into IP addresses, giving them control over which server a user may access via a given domain.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] Below the root, Internet resources are organized into a hierarchy of domains, administered by the respective registrars and domain name holders.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] A DNS name server is a server that stores the DNS records, such as address (A, AAAA) records, name server (NS) records, and mail exchanger (MX) records for a domain name (see also List of DNS record types) and responds with answers to queries against its database.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] Name servers are usually either *authoritative* or *recursive*, as described below.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] Although not the usual practice today, name servers can be both authoritative *and* recursive, if they are configured to give authoritative answers to queries in some zones, while acting as a caching name server for all other zones.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] An authoritative name server is a name server that is responsible for giving answers in response to questions asked about names in a zone.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] An authoritative-only name server returns answers only to queries about domain names for which it is responsible (as specifically configured by its administrator).
[src:aws-route53/name-server] A primary server for a zone is the server that stores the definitive versions of all records in that zone.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] It is identified in the start-of-authority (SOA) resource record.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] A secondary server for a zone uses an automatic updating mechanism to maintain an identical copy of the primary server's database for a zone.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] Examples of such mechanisms include DNS zone transfers and file transfer protocols.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] DNS provides a mechanism whereby the primary for a zone can notify all the known secondaries for that zone when the contents of the zone have changed.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] The contents of a zone are either manually configured by an administrator, or managed using Dynamic DNS.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] Every domain name appears in a zone served by one or more authoritative name servers.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] The fully qualified domain names of the authoritative name servers of a zone are listed in the NS records of that zone.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] If the server for a zone is not also authoritative for its parent zone, the server for the parent zone must be configured with a delegation for the zone.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] When a domain is registered with a domain name registrar, the zone administrator provides the list of name servers (typically at least two, for redundancy) that are authoritative for the zone that contains the domain.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] The registrar provides the names of these servers to the domain registry for the top-level domain containing the zone.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] The domain registry in turn configures the authoritative name servers for that top-level domain with delegations for each server for the zone.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] A name server indicates that its response is authoritative by setting the *Authoritative Answer* (*AA*) bit in the response to a query on a name for which it is authoritative.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] Name servers providing answers for which they are not authoritative (for example, name servers for parent zones or recursive resolvers) do not set the *AA* bit.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] A *Recursive Resolver* (sometimes called a Recursive Name Server) is a DNS name server that accepts recursive queries (defined below) from clients (who are using a stub resolver), and then resolves those queries, either from a cache of prior results, or by asking one or more authoritative servers.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] If a name server cannot answer a query because it does not contain an entry for the host in its DNS cache, it may recursively query name servers higher up in the hierarchy.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] This is known as a *recursive query* or *recursive lookup*.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] A server providing recursive queries is known as a *recursive name server*.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] In principle, authoritative name servers suffice for the operation of the Internet.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] However, with only authoritative name-servers operating, every DNS query must start with recursive queries at the root zone of the Domain Name System and each user system must implement resolver software capable of recursive operation.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] A **caching name server** or **DNS cache** is usually a recursive resolver that stores DNS query results for a period of time determined in the configuration (time-to-live) of each domain-name record.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] DNS caches improve the efficiency of the DNS by reducing DNS traffic across the Internet, and by reducing load on authoritative name-servers, particularly root name-servers.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] Because they can answer questions more quickly, they also increase the performance of end-user applications that use the DNS.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] Caching name servers are often also recursive name servers—they perform every step necessary to answer any DNS query they receive.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] To do this, the name server queries each authoritative name server in turn, starting from the DNS root zone.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] It continues until it reaches the authoritative server for the zone that contains the queried domain name.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] That server provides the answer to the question, or definitively says it can't be answered, and the *caching resolver* then returns this response to the client that asked the question.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] The authority, resolving and caching functions can all be present in a DNS server implementation, but this is not required: a DNS server can implement any one of these functions alone, without implementing the others.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] Internet service providers typically provide caching resolvers for their customers.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] In addition, many home-networking routers implement caching resolvers to improve efficiency in the local network.
[src:aws-route53/name-server] In some systems, `nscd` (name service caching daemon) provides a comprehensive name caching mechanism.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] In its simplest implementation, round-robin DNS works by responding to DNS requests not only with a single potential IP address, but with a list of potential IP addresses corresponding to several servers that host identical services.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] The order in which IP addresses from the list are returned is the basis for the term *round robin*.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] With each DNS response, the IP address sequence in the list is permuted.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] Traditionally, IP clients initially attempt connections with the first address returned from a DNS query, so that on different connection attempts, clients would receive service from different providers, thus distributing the overall load among servers.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] Some resolvers attempt to re-order the list to give priority to numerically "closer" networks.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] This behaviour was standardized in RFC 3484 during the definition of IPv6.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] When applied to IPv4, a bug in Windows Vista caused issues and defeated round-robin load-balancing.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] Some desktop clients do try alternate addresses after a connection timeout of up to 30 seconds.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] Round-robin DNS is often used to load balance requests among a number of web servers.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] For example, a company has one domain name and three identical copies of the same web site residing on three servers with three IP addresses.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] The DNS server will be set up so that domain name has multiple A records, one for each IP address.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] When one user accesses the home page it will be sent to the first IP address.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] The second user who accesses the home page will be sent to the next IP address, and the third user will be sent to the third IP address.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] In each case, once the IP address is given out, it goes to the end of the list.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] The fourth user, therefore, will be sent to the first IP address, and so forth.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] A round-robin DNS name is, on rare occasions, referred to as a "rotor" due to the rotation among alternative A records.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] Although easy to implement, round-robin DNS has a number of drawbacks, such as those arising from record caching in the DNS hierarchy itself, as well as client-side address caching and reuse, the combination of which can be difficult to manage.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] Round-robin DNS should not solely be relied upon for service availability.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] If a service at one of the addresses in the list fails, the DNS will continue to hand out that address and clients will still attempt to reach the inoperable service.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] Round-robin DNS may not be the best choice for load balancing on its own, since it merely alternates the order of the address records each time a name server is queried.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] Because it does not take transaction time, server load, and network congestion into consideration, it works best for services with a large number of uniformly distributed connections to servers of equivalent capacity.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] Otherwise, it just does load distribution.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] Methods exist to overcome such limitations.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] For example, modified DNS servers (such as lbnamed) can routinely poll mirrored servers for availability and load factor.
[src:aws-route53/round-robin-dns] If a server does not reply as required, the server can be temporarily removed from the DNS pool, until it reports that it is once again operating within specs.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] Under the Internet Protocol, TTL is an 8-bit field.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] In the IPv4 header, TTL is the 9th octet of 20.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] In the IPv6 header, it is the 8th octet of 40.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] The maximum TTL value is 255, the maximum value of a single octet.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] The time-to-live value can be thought of as an upper bound on the time that an IP datagram can exist in an Internet system.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] The TTL field is set by the sender of the datagram, and reduced by every router on the route to its destination.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] If the TTL field reaches zero before the datagram arrives at its destination, then the datagram is discarded and an Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) error datagram (11 - Time Exceeded) is sent back to the sender.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] The purpose of the TTL field is to avoid a situation in which an undeliverable datagram keeps circulating on an Internet system, and such a system eventually becoming swamped by such "immortals".
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] In theory, under IPv4, time to live is measured in seconds, although every host that passes the datagram must reduce the TTL by at least one unit.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] In practice, the TTL field is reduced by one on every hop.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] To reflect this practice, the field is renamed *hop limit* in IPv6.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] TTLs also occur in the Domain Name System (DNS), where they are set by an authoritative name server for a particular resource record.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] When a caching (recursive) nameserver queries the authoritative nameserver for a resource record, it will cache that record for the time (in seconds) specified by the TTL.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] If a stub resolver queries the caching nameserver for the same record before the TTL has expired, the caching server will simply reply with the already cached resource record rather than retrieve it from the authoritative nameserver again.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] TTL for NXDOMAIN (non-existent domain) responses is set from the minimum of the MINIMUM field of the SOA record and the TTL of the SOA itself, and indicates how long a resolver may cache the negative answer.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] Shorter TTLs can cause heavier loads on an authoritative name server, but can be useful when changing the address of critical services like web servers or MX records, and therefore are often lowered by the DNS administrator prior to a service being moved, in order to reduce possible disruptions.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] An older common TTL value for DNS was 86400 seconds, which is 24 hours.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] A TTL value of 86400 would mean that, if a DNS record was changed on the authoritative nameserver, DNS servers around the world could still be showing the old value from their cache for up to 24 hours after the last update by client.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] Newer DNS methods that are part of a disaster recovery (DR) system may have some records deliberately set extremely low on TTL.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] For example, a 300-second TTL would help key records expire in 5 minutes to help ensure these records are flushed quickly worldwide.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] This gives administrators the ability to edit and update records in a timely manner.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] TTL values are "per record" and setting this value on specific records is sometimes honored automatically by all standard DNS systems worldwide.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] However, a problem persists in that some caching DNS nameservers set their own TTLs regardless of the authoritative records, thus it cannot be guaranteed that all downstream DNS servers have the new records after the TTL has expired.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] Time to live may also be expressed as the date and time on which a record expires.
[src:aws-route53/time-to-live] The `Expires:` header in HTTP responses, the `Cache-Control: max-age` header field in both requests and responses and the `expires` field in HTTP cookies express time-to-live in this way.
